==English==
===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''[[cascade#French|cascade]]'', from {{It.}} ''[[cascata]]'', from ''[[cascare]]'' to fall

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪd|-eɪd]]

===Noun===
'''cascade'''  (''plural'' '''[[cascades]]''')
#A fall of water over a precipice, as in a river or brook; a [[waterfall]] less than a cataract.
#:''Now murm'ring soft, now roaring in '''cascade'''.''  -Cawper
#(''figurative'') A stream or sequence of a thing or things occurring as if falling like a cascade.
#:''The rise in serotonin levels sets off a '''cascade''' of chemical events'' &mdash; Richard M. Restak, ''The Secret Life of the Brain'', Joseph Henry Press, 2001

===Intransitive verb===
